		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The Steroids of Middle-earth<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=14360'>Joseph "Quickbeam" Conley</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=14360&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 21, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> In the lands of major-league LOTR, the days were dark and clouded with suspicion. Bulked-up cards grew stronger and stronger, hammering opposition into the dust. For something had scarred its tender countenance: Supplements to up the offensive output. <br />
Each owner relied on powerful cards to win games, day after day. Flaming Brands, No Strangers, Aragorn, HTTWC, and more made beating them nearly impossible. <br />
The commissioners of the LOTR TCG got scared, and held a council. It was decided that such cards would be ‘banned’ thus apparently leveling the playing field and giving equal opportunity to all decks. 		<br />
Unfortunately, the commissioners failed to take on thing into context: They were not God, and thus were unable to act like him. As new versions of the game were released, more cards became overpowered. Some were powerful yet not too much, like the oft-discussed Dauntless Hunter. A particularly abusive card like ‘Merry’s Sword’ was despised by all except the greedy owners who flaunted him to the fullest of his abilities. <br />
So again the commissioners gathered, and decided to do something called ‘random testing’ to determine which cards were too powerful – suspiciously so. Certain cards would then be placed on a ‘watch list’, and then, depending upon their subsequent decision, be either banned or ignored. <br />
Then a new set was released and everything went haywire. Suddenly powerful decks became not-quite-so-powerful. The Pirates and Besiegers became the talk of the LOTR community. <br />
As these events took place, a young man named Lou strove desperately to build himself a deck that would win. After his pounding at the skilled hands of Mike French, and the fame of his ‘Stupid Swarm’ deck, everyone began teching against it. Curse Their Foul Feet, Ranger of the North, What Are They? and more reigned supreme, and Lou was forced to retire his deck. <br />
Now, however, things were a little different. Having won plenty of tournaments, the contents of his binder had heightened considerably. Also Lou had managed to get a rather ludicrous job, enabling him to buy quite a few boxes online. Two of these had been Siege of Gondor, thus supplying him with most of the rares he would need. Also, through an Ebay deal he had gotten 4 of just about every common and uncommon every printed. Five binders lay before him, engorged with cards. Lou wearily took a sip of Coke, and waited for the caffeine to kick it. It didn’t. He looked over at the clock. 1:35 A.M. In just nine hours he would be playing in a TOC – and he still had no idea what to play. <br />
Lou had toyed with many ideas, but competent FP’s sides, in his opinion, needed to counter every shadow side out there. And by the time he’d done that his Free Peoples side had about 50 cards in it. For Lou, despite his fame, had a vital flaw: He was inexperienced in deck-building. In play, yes, few could match him. But at the building of the decks... <br />
Lou slapped his face a few more times, then went over to his bedroom window and pulled it open. He stuck his head outside and breathed several deep lungfulls of the cool night air. His head slightly cleared from drowsiness, and he wished in his head that whoever that majestic voice was before would give him a hand. <br />
On cue, a beam of light shone down from the sky and dazzled him. Lou blinked and picked up a pair of cheap sunglasses. <br />
“You, again,” he said, clearly delighted. <br />
“Me,” said the majestic voice. <br />
“Does this mean I can summon you by just wishing?” Lou asked. <br />
“Not on your life,” the majestic voice growled, suddenly not sounding quite as majestic. “It just so happened that I was bored and I just got finished watching ‘Survivor’, so – ”<br />
“Hold it, ‘Survivor’ is on Thursday,” Lou pointed out. 	<br />
“I was out of town, my aunt taped it for me,” the majestic voice said. “I swear, if you correct me or say another stupid thing I’m out of here.” <br />
“Sorry,” Lou was quick to say. “Nice to see you – well, hear you again.” <br />
“Let’s dispense with the pleasantries,” the majestic voice snarled. “You got beat by Mike French, didn’t you?” <br />
“Yes,” Lou said regretfully. <br />
“Don’t let it happen again.” <br />
“I’ll try not to.” <br />
“No. Do. Or do not. There is no try.” <br />
“Hey, you stole that line.” <br />
“It’s the one line of dialogue worth remembering in the entire ’Wars trilogy, ain’t it?” <br />
“True,” Lou said. <br />
“So let’s get the obvious stuff out of the way,” the majestic voice said. “I know you want to be asleep. We’ll get to that.” <br />
“I have a tournament in nine hours and I haven’t even started,” Lou said. <br />
“Well, it’s tough to get more obvious than that. You need help, kid. So, what do you think people will be playing?” <br />
“Corsairs, Besiegers, and threat Nazgul,” Lou said. “A couple Isen Orc swarms, some Beasterlings, maybe a random Uruk deck, a Dunland or two, could be a Moria. That’s seven things.” <br />
“Right,” said the majestic voice. “Well, who’s the guy who has counters for everything?” <br />
“Gandalf,” Lou said. <br />
“Right. So, to save deck space, we’ll use Leader of Men so you can start him and two more twilight.” <br />
“Don’t have Leader of Men,” Lou said. <br />
“You can trade for one from your friend on the trip over there,” the majestic voice said. “Bring your foil Aragorn. He’s had his eye on that one.” <br />
Lou grabbed a pen and paper and scribbled down Gandalf, Leader of Men. <br />
“First off, let’s deal with Corsairs. Obviously they revolved around their ships. So let’s pack three copies of Roll of Thunder to get rid of them. The Rolls are doubly good because they can also get rid of Hides, Uruk spears, Winged Mounts, and Polearms. Since you’re starting Gandalf, let’s use two copies of Glamdring – the old one, which lets us look at your opponent’s hand, remove pool against Besiegers and Moria, and Stupid Swarm. We’ll use the old Gandalf’s staff for help against giant Besiegers, and Narya because it’s Narya.” <br />
Lou quickly finished writing it all down. <br />
“How many copies of Terrible and Evil do you have?” the majestic voice asked. <br />
“Three,” Lou said. <br />
“Add them all. Then put in two copies of Fireworks to recycle your great events back through. What’s the card total now?” <br />
Lou finished, and tallied. This is what his paper looked like: <br />
<br />
Gandalf, Leader of Men<br />
Roll of Thunder x3<br />
Glamdring x2<br />
Gandalf’s Staff<br />
Narya<br />
Terrible and Evil x3<br />
Fireworks x2 <br />
<br />
“13 cards so far. A little over a third of my deck.” <br />
“And you’ve countered three Shadow sides reasonably well. Now for your starting companion, none better than Arwen, Fair Elf Maiden. Tell me you’ve got her.” <br />
“One copy,” Lou said. “Just pulled her the other day. Man, she is hot.” <br />
“You can say that again,” said the majestic voice. “Start her. Also put in Asfaloth, the old one, and two copies of Gwemegil which puts out a tank against Nazgul and Uruk Trackers and all other fierce guys. And to counter the Stupid Swarm you should add two copies of Curse Their Foul Feet which will also kick off against Besiegers and Moria. Do you have a copy of Greenleaf?” <br />
“Yeah, my grandparents bought the Fellowship DVD thingy a while back and mailed me the three cards.” <br />
“Right, put in Greenleaf, he’s good against anything. Update?” <br />
Lou counted. “We’re at 20. About 15 to go.” <br />
“How many Aragorn, Ranger of the North’s do you have?” <br />
“I have two.” <br />
“At the tournament tomorrow there’ll be a dude with metal-rimmed glasses, a small goatee, and blue eyes. You can trade him foils for the next two copies. Just tell him you’re trying to get the cards to build some deck while stroking the one you have. And he’ll also trade you a copy of Anduril, Flame of the West, another card you need.” <br />
“How do you know all that?” <br />
“If I told you, I’d have to kill you,” the majestic voice said. “So don’t ask. Now, for a fifth companion, put in three copies of Boromir, Defender of Minas Tirith, and his sword. And then Dervorin to help out with double-moving. Though you shouldn’t go above five companions unless you have at least one copy of Terrible and Evil in hand, for Enquea protection. Total?” <br />
“Thirty cards.” <br />
“Right. Sam, Son of Hamfast to whack burdens, Sting, BOTEL for Frodo, and two copies of Grown Suddenly Tall to get rid of the pesky conditions, plus Have Patience to heal Gandalf, bringing the total in at a respectable 35 cards.” <br />
“Speaking of ‘for Frodo’, we haven’t decided which one of those to use, or the Ring,” Lou said. “Which are the best?” <br />
“The best Ring is the Marshmallow Ring,” the majestic voice said. <br />
“The Marshmallow Ring?” <br />
“Unfortunately it hasn’t been released yet. So we’ll go with the Bane, and use the 12-resistance Frodo since none of the other seem to particularly pop out at me.”<br />
“So what about the Shadow side?” Lou asked. <br />
“Getting bit too hasty, aren’t we? Haven’t finished with the FP’s side yet. It still needs a bit more, particularly pumps. Let’s trim Dervorin, Sam, and one copy of Fireworks, and add two copies of Trust Me and a Have Patience for added healing of Gandalf, leaving the total still at 35.” <br />
“Why’d you tell me to add Dervorin and Sam if you were just going to take them out later?” Lou asked, annoyed. <br />
“I’m hoping that you’ll understand the thought process of deckbuilding and I won’t have to keep coming back,” said the majestic voice, sounding a bit pissed off. “So now you should switch Frodo to Wicked Masster! for the Gandalf signet.”<br />
“Right.” Lou made the change. <br />
“For the Shadow, your choices are limited because of your card pool,” the majestic voice said. “But since I know you’ve been collecting them, I say to run Corsairs. Although other people may be using Gandalf, I think most will be either using Rohan, Knights with Catapult, Elf/Gondor, or What Are They? And I’m getting tired of talking.” <br />
Suddenly, faint golden lines began appear on Lou’s notebook. They shone brighter and brighter, and tiny golden letters began to form: <br />
<br />
Castamir of Umbar x4 <br />
Wind That Sped Ships x4<br />
Black Sails of Umbar x4<br />
Corsair Plunderer x3<br />
Black Numenorean x4<br />
Corsair Gunners x3<br />
Corsair Buccaneer x3<br />
Corsair Marauder x4<br />
Ships of Great Draught x2<br />
Ulaire Enquea, Lieutenant of Morgul <br />
Corsair War Galley x3<br />
<br />
“Add tokens, get initiative, play guys for cheap, make them strength +6 and then recycle your events so you can use them every turn. On top of that you get to discard possessions like Merry’s Sword and their bows so Ulaire Enquea can kill people, it doesn’t get much more fun than that,” said the majestic voice. “Lou, with this deck you can take down everyone in your path. Don’t screw it up, alright?” <br />
“Right. Thanks,” Lou said. <br />
With a flash of light, the beam disappeared, leaving Lou with his head outside his window and a notebook and pen in his hands. <br />
Quickly he put the deck together, and filled his binder with the foils he needed to trade for the last few cards. Lou caught a few hours of sleep, and then got up early enough to make his way to the TOC. As he waited outside his apartment for his friend to show up with the car, Lou thought of what would happen if it got out that he was taking advice from the celestial ally. <br />
Good thing nobody knows but me or they’d be talking about it all over Decktech, he thought. Of course, nobody would ever believe it. <br />
<br />
- Quickbeam <br />
<br />
With apologies to the Wachowskis, George Lucas, and Bud Selig. (except for the last) <br />
